e of the longest and most controversial bankruptcy in Canadian history. Moving from the frontier areas of northern Ontario to the heart of the continental economy, Corporate Cataclysm shows how competitive strategies, industrial organization, corporate finance, and law combined with the empire-building dreams of entrepreneurs and the concerns of politicians to generate an economic disaster. It then chronicles the disputes and intense strife that plagued Abitibi’s fourteen-year receivership.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aNewsprint industryzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Pre-Confederation (to 1867).2bisacsh  aAbitibi Power and Paper Limited.  aCanadian business history.  abankruptcy.  abusiness and government.  acorporate failure.  acorporate reorganization.  aforestry.  ainsolvency.  anewsprint.  apulp and paper.  areceivership.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753231440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487532314423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487532314.jpg  a978-3-11-069045-3  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles